  "prompt": "Is the Tamil language older than Sanskrit? How old is it when compared to all other languages of the world?",
  "response": "The question of the age of Tamil is complex and has been a subject of scholarly debate. Here's a detailed overview:\n\n1. Age of Tamil:\n- Classical Tamil literature dates back to around 300 BCE\n- Sangam literature period is estimated between 300 BCE to 300 CE\n- Some linguistic scholars argue that spoken Tamil might be much older\n\n2. Comparison with Sanskrit:\n- Sanskrit is generally considered older than Tamil\n- Sanskrit's earliest texts (Vedic Sanskrit) date back to around 1500-1200 BCE\n- Tamil developed independently, with less external influence compared to Sanskrit\n\n3. Global Language Age Ranking:\n- Sanskrit is among the oldest documented languages\n- Tamil is considered one of the oldest classical languages in the world\n- Other ancient languages include:\n  * Sumerian (circa 3000 BCE)\n  * Egyptian (circa 3000 BCE)\n  * Chinese (circa 1200 BCE)\n  * Greek (circa 1450 BCE)\n  * Hebrew (circa 1000 BCE)\n\n4. Expert Perspectives:\n- While exact origins are debated, Tamil is recognized as a classical language with a rich literary tradition\n- It's considered one of the longest-surviving classical languages with continuous literary production\n\nThe precise age of spoken Tamil remains uncertain, but its documented history is well-established.",
